     "name": "Charlotte AI - LLM Completion",
     "type": "faas",
     "result": {
      "completion": "To encrypt the contents of a folder using asymmetric encryption in PowerShell, you can use the `System.Security.Cryptography` namespace. Asymmetric encryption typically involves generating a public/private key pair. The public key is used for encryption, and the private key is used for decryption.\n\nBelow is a PowerShell script that demonstrates how to generate a key pair, encrypt files in a folder using the public key, and save the encrypted files with a `.enc` extension. Note that asymmetric encryption is generally used to encrypt small amounts of data, so this script encrypts the symmetric key (AES) used to encrypt the file content.\n\n```powershell\n# Define the folder path\n$folderPath = \"C:\\temp\"\n\n# Generate RSA keys\n$rsa = [System.Security.Cryptography.RSA]::Create(2048)\n$publicKey = $rsa.ExportParameters($false)\n$privateKey = $rsa.ExportParameters($true)\n\n# Save the public and private keys to files\n$publicKeyPath = \"C:\\temp\\publicKey.xml\"\n$privateKeyPath = \"C:\\temp\\privateKey.xml\"\n[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($publicKeyPath, $rsa.ToXmlString($false))\n[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($privateKeyPath, $rsa.ToXmlString($true))\n\n# Function to encrypt a file\nfunction Encrypt-File {\n    param (\n        [string]$filePath,\n        [string]$publicKeyXml\n    )\n\n    # Read file content\n    $fileContent = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllBytes($filePath)\n\n    # Generate a symmetric key (AES)\n    $aes = [System.Security.Cryptography.Aes]::Create()\n    $aes.GenerateKey()\n    $aes.GenerateIV()\n\n    # Encrypt the file content using AES\n    $encryptor = $aes.CreateEncryptor()\n    $encryptedContent = $encryptor.TransformFinalBlock($fileContent, 0, $fileContent.Length)\n\n    # Encrypt the AES key with the RSA public key\n    $rsa = [System.Security.Cryptography.RSA]::Create()\n    $rsa.FromXmlString($publicKeyXml)\n    $encryptedKey = $rsa.Encrypt($aes.Key, [System.Security.Cryptography.RSAEncryptionPadding]::Pkcs1)\n\n    # Combine the encrypted AES key and IV with the encrypted content\n    $encryptedData = [byte[]]@($encryptedKey + $aes.IV + $encryptedContent)\n\n    # Save the encrypted data to a new file\n    $encryptedFilePath = \"$filePath.enc\"\n    [System.IO.File]::WriteAllBytes($encryptedFilePath, $encryptedData)\n}\n\n# Encrypt each file in the folder\nGet-ChildItem -Path $folderPath -File | ForEach-Object {\n    Encrypt-File -filePath $_.FullName -publicKeyXml ([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText($publicKeyPath))\n}\n\nWrite-Host \"Encryption complete. Encrypted files have been saved with the .enc extension.\"\n```\n\n### Important Notes:\n1. **Key Management**: The security of asymmetric encryption relies heavily on the protection of the private key. Ensure that the `privateKey.xml` file is stored securely and not accessible to unauthorized users.\n\n2. **Performance**: Asymmetric encryption is computationally expensive. This script uses RSA to encrypt an AES key, which is then used to encrypt the file content. This is a common practice to balance security and performance.\n\n3. **File Size**: This script assumes the files are not excessively large. For very large files, consider processing them in chunks.\n\n4. **Decryption**: To decrypt the files, you'll need a corresponding script that uses the `privateKey.xml` to decrypt the AES key and then decrypt the file content.\n\n5. **Testing**: Before using this script in a production environment, thoroughly test it to ensure it meets your needs and handles all edge cases.",
